1 If the matter that the Department seeks to obtain by subpoena is located outside the State, the
2 entity or person subpoenaed may make it available to the Department or its representative to
3 examine the matter at the place where it is located. The Department may designate
4 representatives, including officials of the state in which the matter is located, to inspect the matter
5 on its behalf, and may respond to similar requests from officials of other states.
6 Upon failure of an entity or person without lawful excuse to obey a subpoena and upon
7 reasonable notice to all persons affected, the Department may apply to the superior court for an
8 order compelling compliance.
9 The Department may request that an entity or person that refuses to comply with a subpoena
10 on the ground that testimony or matter may incriminate the entity or person be ordered by the
11 court to provide the testimony or matter. Except in a prosecution for perjury, an entity or
12 individual that complies with a court order to provide testimony or matter after asserting a valid
13 privilege against self-incrimination shall not have the testimony or matter so provided, or
14 evidence derived therefrom, received against the entity or person in any criminal investigation or
15 proceeding.
16 Any entity or person upon whom a subpoena is served pursuant to this subsection shall
17 comply with the terms thereof unless otherwise provided by order of the court.
18 Any entity or person that fails to appear with the intent to avoid, evade, or prevent compliance
19 in whole or in part with any investigation under this Chapter or who removes from any place,
20 conceals, withholds, mutilates, alters, or destroys, or by any other means falsifies any
21 documentary material in the possession, custody, or control of any entity or person subject to any
22 such subpoena, or knowingly conceals any relevant information with the intent to avoid, evade,
23 or prevent compliance shall be liable for a civil penalty of not more than five thousand dollars
24 ($5,000) per week in violation, reasonable attorneys' fees, and costs.
25 (e) Rules. – The Department may adopt rules to implement this Chapter.
26 (f) Civil Penalties. – The clear proceeds of civil penalties provided for in this section
27 shall be remitted to the Civil Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2.
28 "§ 114B-3. Age verification for social media platforms.
29 (a) A social media platform must use either anonymous age verification or standard age
30 verification to verify that an account holder is 16 years of age or older and, except as provided in
31 G.S. 114B-2(b), prevent creation of an account by a person younger than 16 years of age. The
32 social media platform must offer anonymous age verification and standard age verification, and
33 a person attempting to create an account may select which method will be used to verify the
34 person's age.
35 (b) A social media platform must ensure that the requirements of subsection (c) of this
36 section are met.
37 (c) A third party conducting anonymous age verification pursuant to this section must
38 comply with all of the following:
39 (1) Shall not retain personal identifying information used to verify age once the
40 age of an account holder or a person seeking an account has been verified.
41 (2) Shall not use personal identifying information used to verify age for any other
42 purpose.
43 (3) Must keep anonymous any personal identifying information used to verify
44 age. The information may not be shared or otherwise communicated to any
45 person.
46 (4) Must protect personal identifying information used to verify age from
47 unauthorized or illegal access, destruction, use, modification, or disclosure
48 through reasonable security procedures and practices appropriate to the nature
49 of the personal information.
Page 4 House Bill 301-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (d) Any violation of subsection (a) or (b) of this section is deemed an unfair and deceptive
2 trade practice actionable under Chapter 75 of the General Statutes solely by the Department on
3 behalf of a resident minor against a social media platform.
4 If the Department has reason to believe that a social media platform is in violation, the
5 Department may bring an action against the social media platform for an unfair or deceptive act
6 or practice under Chapter 75 of the General Statutes. In addition to other remedies allowed by
7 law, the Department may collect a civil penalty of up to fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) per
8 violation and reasonable attorneys' fees and court costs.
9 When the social media platform's failure to comply with subsection (a) or (b) of this section
10 is a consistent pattern of knowing or reckless conduct, punitive damages may be assessed against
11 the social media platform.
12 "§ 114B-4. Miscellaneous provisions.
13 (a) It is the intent of the General Assembly that this Chapter be liberally construed for the
14 protection of minors.
15 (b) If any provision of this Chapter or its application to any person or circumstances is
16 held invalid, the invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this Chapter which
17 can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to this end, the provisions of
18 this Chapter are severable."
19 SECTION 2. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025.
